concept_explanation.intro:
**Abstract class**: a class that cannot be instantiated directly. Declared with the `abstract` keyword.

**Abstract method**: a method with no body, declared with `abstract`. Subclasses MUST implement it.

```java
public abstract class Shape {
    protected String color;

    public Shape(String color) {
        this.color = color;
    }

    // Abstract method — no body, no { }
    // Subclasses MUST implement this
    public abstract double area();

    // Concrete method — has a body, shared by all subclasses
    public void printInfo() {
        System.out.println(color + " shape, area=" + area());
    }
}
```

Three key observations:
1. `abstract class Shape` — cannot do `new Shape()`. Compilation error.
2. `public abstract double area()` — method ends with `;`, no body at all.
3. `printInfo()` is a CONCRETE (non-abstract) method with a full body — shared by all subclasses.

concept_explanation.must_implement:
Any concrete class extending an abstract class MUST implement all abstract methods:

```java
class Circle extends Shape {
    private double radius;

    public Circle(String color, double radius) {
        super(color);
        this.radius = radius;
    }

    @Override
    public double area() {          // MUST implement — concrete class
        return Math.PI * radius * radius;
    }
}

class Rectangle extends Shape {
    private double width, height;

    public Rectangle(String color, double width, double height) {
        super(color);
        this.width = width;
        this.height = height;
    }

    @Override
    public double area() {          // MUST implement
        return width * height;
    }
}
```

If Circle DOESN'T implement `area()`, the compiler errors: 'Circle is not abstract and does not override abstract method area() in Shape.'

**The contract is enforced**: you literally cannot create a concrete subclass without implementing the required methods. This is the power — it's impossible to accidentally forget.

concept_explanation.partial_abstract:
An abstract class can have BOTH abstract and concrete methods. Concrete methods in the abstract class are shared by all subclasses — no duplication.

```java
public abstract class Employee {
    // Concrete shared fields
    protected final int id;
    protected String name;
    private static int nextId = 1;

    // Concrete constructor — shared
    public Employee(String name) {
        this.id = nextId++;
        this.name = name;
    }

    // Concrete getters — shared
    public int getId() { return id; }
    public String getName() { return name; }

    // ABSTRACT method — each subclass must define their own salary
    public abstract double calculateSalary();

    // Concrete method using the abstract one — TEMPLATE METHOD pattern
    public void printPayslip() {
        System.out.println("Payslip for " + name + ": ₹" + calculateSalary());
    }
}

class Developer extends Employee {
    private double baseSalary;
    private double stockBonus;

    public Developer(String name, double base, double bonus) {
        super(name);
        this.baseSalary = base;
        this.stockBonus = bonus;
    }

    @Override
    public double calculateSalary() {  // MUST implement
        return baseSalary + stockBonus;
    }
}

// Usage:
Employee emp = new Developer("Aisha", 80000, 15000);
emp.printPayslip();  // 'Payslip for Aisha: ₹95000.0'
```

The concrete `printPayslip()` calls the abstract `calculateSalary()`. At runtime, the real implementation (Developer's) runs. The abstract class provides the skeleton; subclasses fill the substance.

concept_explanation.template_method_pattern:
The **Template Method** pattern is one of the most important design patterns, and it's built entirely on abstract classes:

> **The parent class defines the algorithm skeleton. Abstract methods are the steps. Subclasses fill in the steps.**

```java
public abstract class DataProcessor {

    // Template method — defines the algorithm
    // Marked final so subclasses can't change the algorithm itself
    public final void process() {
        readData();      // step 1
        validateData();  // step 2
        transformData(); // step 3  
        writeData();     // step 4
        logResult();     // step 5
    }

    // Steps that ALL processors implement the same way
    private void logResult() {
        System.out.println("Processing completed by " + getClass().getSimpleName());
    }

    // Abstract steps — each processor implements differently
    protected abstract void readData();
    protected abstract void validateData();
    protected abstract void transformData();
    protected abstract void writeData();
}

class CSVProcessor extends DataProcessor {
    @Override
    protected void readData()      { System.out.println("Reading CSV..."); }
    @Override
    protected void validateData()  { System.out.println("Validating CSV format..."); }
    @Override
    protected void transformData() { System.out.println("Transforming CSV to records..."); }
    @Override
    protected void writeData()     { System.out.println("Writing records to DB..."); }
}

class JSONProcessor extends DataProcessor {
    @Override
    protected void readData()      { System.out.println("Fetching JSON from API..."); }
    @Override
    protected void validateData()  { System.out.println("Validating JSON schema..."); }
    @Override
    protected void transformData() { System.out.println("Mapping JSON fields..."); }
    @Override
    protected void writeData()     { System.out.println("Inserting into MongoDB..."); }
}

// Usage — same call, different behavior:
new CSVProcessor().process();
new JSONProcessor().process();
```

The `process()` method is the same for all processors. What differs is HOW each step is done. New processor type? Extend DataProcessor, implement the four steps. The algorithm never changes.

Real Java uses: Android's Activity lifecycle (onCreate, onStart, onResume), HTTP servlets, JUnit's TestCase, Spring MVC's AbstractController.

concept_explanation.abstract_in_chain:
An abstract class CAN extend another abstract class without implementing its abstract methods:

```java
public abstract class Vehicle {
    public abstract void fuelUp();
    public abstract void accelerate();
}

public abstract class MotorVehicle extends Vehicle {
    protected int horsePower;

    public MotorVehicle(int hp) { this.horsePower = hp; }

    @Override
    public void fuelUp() { System.out.println("Fueling up motor vehicle..."); }
    // Note: accelerate() still abstract — MotorVehicle doesn't implement it
}

public class Car extends MotorVehicle {
    public Car(int hp) { super(hp); }

    @Override
    public void accelerate() {
        System.out.println("Car accelerates with " + horsePower + "hp");
    }
    // fuelUp() inherited from MotorVehicle (concrete there)
}
```

The abstract method `accelerate()` propagates down until a CONCRETE class provides the implementation. The chain can be as deep as needed.

step_by_step_solution.details:
```java
public abstract class Shape {
    protected String color;

    public Shape(String color) {
        this.color = color;
    }

    // Abstract — subclasses must compute their own area
    public abstract double area();

    // Abstract — subclasses must describe themselves
    public abstract String describe();

    // Concrete — shared by ALL shapes
    public String getColor() { return color; }

    public void printInfo() {
        System.out.printf("%s (area=%.2f)%n", describe(), area());
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return describe() + " [area=" + String.format("%.2f", area()) + "]";
    }
}
```

Now `area()` and `describe()` have no body. The concrete `printInfo()` calls BOTH abstract methods — they resolve to the subclass implementations at runtime. `new Shape('red')` is now a compile error.

```java
class Circle extends Shape {
    private double radius;

    public Circle(String color, double radius) {
        super(color);
        this.radius = radius;
    }

    @Override
    public double area() { return Math.PI * radius * radius; }

    @Override
    public String describe() {
        return color + " Circle(r=" + radius + ")";
    }
}

class Rectangle extends Shape {
    private double width, height;

    public Rectangle(String color, double width, double height) {
        super(color);
        this.width = width;
        this.height = height;
    }

    @Override
    public double area() { return width * height; }

    @Override
    public String describe() {
        return color + " Rectangle(" + width + "x" + height + ")";
    }
}

class Triangle extends Shape {
    private double base, height;

    public Triangle(String color, double base, double height) {
        super(color);
        this.base = base;
        this.height = height;
    }

    @Override
    public double area() { return 0.5 * base * height; }

    @Override
    public String describe() {
        return color + " Triangle(b=" + base + ", h=" + height + ")";
    }
}
```

```java
public abstract class ReportGenerator {

    // Template method — fixed algorithm, sealed with 'final'
    public final String generate(String[][] data) {
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        sb.append(header());
        sb.append("\n");
        for (String[] row : data) {
            sb.append(formatRow(row[0], row[1]));
            sb.append("\n");
        }
        sb.append(footer());
        return sb.toString();
    }

    // Abstract steps — each format implements differently
    protected abstract String header();
    protected abstract String formatRow(String key, String value);
    protected abstract String footer();
}
```

The `generate()` method is `final` — no subclass can change the algorithm. The three abstract methods are what varies.

```java
class PlainTextReport extends ReportGenerator {
    private String title;

    public PlainTextReport(String title) { this.title = title; }

    @Override
    protected String header() { return "=== " + title + " ==="; }

    @Override
    protected String formatRow(String key, String value) {
        return String.format("%-20s: %s", key, value);
    }

    @Override
    protected String footer() { return "=== End of Report ==="; }
}

class HtmlReport extends ReportGenerator {
    private String title;

    public HtmlReport(String title) { this.title = title; }

    @Override
    protected String header() { 
        return "<html><body><h1>" + title + "</h1><table>"; 
    }

    @Override
    protected String formatRow(String key, String value) {
        return "<tr><td>" + key + "</td><td>" + value + "</td></tr>";
    }

    @Override
    protected String footer() { return "</table></body></html>"; }
}
```

Same method (`generate()`), completely different output. **Zero changes to the algorithm** — only the steps differ.

```java
public static void main(String[] args) {
    // Part 1: Abstract shapes
    Shape[] shapes = {
        new Circle("Red", 5),
        new Rectangle("Blue", 4, 6),
        new Triangle("Green", 3, 8)
    };

    System.out.println("--- Shapes ---");
    for (Shape s : shapes) {
        s.printInfo();
    }
    // new Shape('Red') would be a compile error now

    // Part 2: Report generator
    String[][] reportData = {
        {"Product", "Java Book"},
        {"Price", "₹599"},
        {"Stock", "45"}
    };

    System.out.println("\n--- Plain Text Report ---");
    ReportGenerator textGen = new PlainTextReport("Product Report");
    System.out.println(textGen.generate(reportData));

    System.out.println("--- HTML Report ---");
    ReportGenerator htmlGen = new HtmlReport("Product Report");
    System.out.println(htmlGen.generate(reportData));
}
```

worked_example.final_code:
public abstract class Shape {
    protected String color;

    public Shape(String color) { this.color = color; }

    public abstract double area();
    public abstract String describe();

    public String getColor() { return color; }

    public void printInfo() {
        System.out.printf("%s (area=%.2f)%n", describe(), area());
    }
}

class Circle extends Shape {
    private double radius;
    public Circle(String color, double radius) { super(color); this.radius = radius; }
    @Override public double area() { return Math.PI * radius * radius; }
    @Override public String describe() { return color + " Circle(r=" + radius + ")"; }
}

class Rectangle extends Shape {
    private double width, height;
    public Rectangle(String color, double w, double h) { super(color); width=w; height=h; }
    @Override public double area() { return width * height; }
    @Override public String describe() { return color + " Rectangle(" + width + "x" + height + ")"; }
}

class Triangle extends Shape {
    private double base, height;
    public Triangle(String color, double base, double height) { super(color); this.base=base; this.height=height; }
    @Override public double area() { return 0.5 * base * height; }
    @Override public String describe() { return color + " Triangle(b=" + base + ", h=" + height + ")"; }
}

abstract class ReportGenerator {
    public final String generate(String[][] data) {
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        sb.append(header()).append("\n");
        for (String[] row : data) sb.append(formatRow(row[0], row[1])).append("\n");
        sb.append(footer());
        return sb.toString();
    }
    protected abstract String header();
    protected abstract String formatRow(String key, String value);
    protected abstract String footer();
}

class PlainTextReport extends ReportGenerator {
    private String title;
    PlainTextReport(String t) { title = t; }
    @Override protected String header() { return "=== " + title + " ==="; }
    @Override protected String formatRow(String k, String v) { return String.format("%-20s: %s", k, v); }
    @Override protected String footer() { return "=== End ==="; }
}

class HtmlReport extends ReportGenerator {
    private String title;
    HtmlReport(String t) { title = t; }
    @Override protected String header() { return "<h1>" + title + "</h1><table>"; }
    @Override protected String formatRow(String k, String v) { return "<tr><td>" + k + "</td><td>" + v + "</td></tr>"; }
    @Override protected String footer() { return "</table>"; }
}

public class AbstractDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Shape[] shapes = { new Circle("Red", 5), new Rectangle("Blue", 4, 6), new Triangle("Green", 3, 8) };
        System.out.println("--- Shapes ---");
        for (Shape s : shapes) s.printInfo();

        String[][] data = {{"Product", "Java Book"}, {"Price", "₹599"}, {"Stock", "45"}};
        System.out.println("\n--- Plain ---");
        System.out.println(new PlainTextReport("Report").generate(data));
        System.out.println("--- HTML ---");
        System.out.println(new HtmlReport("Report").generate(data));
    }
}

